<span id="freeTextContainer10667433555486953197">There was so much to love about this one!! Two Vietnamese teens whose parents own rival restaurants across the road...and they accidentally fall in love?! Here for it! The characters referenced themselves to Romeo and Juliet a few times and 😙👌🏻 literal chef&apos;s kiss. It sweeps you into a story of immigration and restaurant culture, with so many sensory details and delicious descriptions you will absolutely feel hungry reading. Linh&apos;s love and passion for art was so palpable and well described too.</span>
  <span id="freeText10667433555486953197" style="display:none">There was so much to love about this one!! Two Vietnamese teens whose parents own rival restaurants across the road...and they accidentally fall in love?! Here for it! The characters referenced themselves to Romeo and Juliet a few times and 😙👌🏻 literal chef's kiss. It sweeps you into a story of immigration and restaurant culture, with so many sensory details and delicious descriptions you will absolutely feel hungry reading. Linh's love and passion for art was so palpable and well described too.<br /><br />Linh and Bao were super cute 🥺 I loved Linh more though, and she does struggle -- both with trying to please her parents who don't want her to be an artist, and figuring out how to live her truth despite lying, and also just working so much and so hard. She was TIRED and also so sweet. Bao found his passion as a writer as the book went on, but he tended to centre himself (even when Linh was breaking down over her parents showing a toxic side, Bao made it about himself? Boy. Sit down.) and never acknowledged his privilege compared to Linh. Still, their love story was gentle and tentative and warm. I could definitely feel Linh's talent as a painter, but Bao's writing not so much 😂 <br /><br />This book made me smile multiple times and had many heartfelt messages. (I recommend the audio!)</span>
